bug.author: y-ich
bug.summary: How can I fix "[TypeInference] Unable to infer type of node "node/name" (XXX)?
bug.description:
<denchmark-h:h2>‚ùìQuestion</denchmark-h>
Hi. I am trying to convert my TensorFlow model using tf-coreml and got errors below for example. <denchmark-code>[TypeInference] Failed to infer type of node "XXX/transpose" (Transpose) </denchmark-code>
I investigated type_inference.py and knew that it is due to the lack of "symbolic_value" attribute in Transpose' inputs (perm or concat in this case). How can I fix these errors? Prior to the errors, I got "Constant Propagation pass failed" message. Is it related with the errors? Thanks.

comments.comment: Hi <denchmark-link:https://github.com/y-ich>@y-ich</denchmark-link> , thanks for reporting this issue! It'd be great if you can file a <denchmark-link:https://github.com/apple/coremltools/issues/new?assignees=&labels=bug&template=---bug-report.md&title=>bug report</denchmark-link> and provide detailed steps, and model files to help us reproduce this issue. Or if you're interested, you can work on a fix for this and contribute back : ). I couldn't comment on the fix because I haven't see the model. but the investigates you did seems to be in the right direction.

<denchmark-link:https://github.com/1duo>@1duo</denchmark-link> san, Thank you for your help! The model is <denchmark-link:https://www.dropbox.com/s/5i4fmc53bvtp3l3/optimized.pb?dl=0>https://www.dropbox.com/s/5i4fmc53bvtp3l3/optimized.pb?dl=0</denchmark-link>
And the script I used is, <denchmark-code>import sys import tfcoreml as tf_converter from coremltools.models import MLModel
if __name__ == "__main__": if len(sys.argv) < 4: print("Usage: python {} source size target_path".format(sys.argv[0])) sys.exit() size = int(sys.argv[2]) tf_converter.convert( tf_model_path=sys.argv[1], mlmodel_path=sys.argv[3], output_feature_names=[ "swa_model/policy_output", "swa_model/value_output", "swa_model/miscvalues_output", "swa_model/scorebelief_output", "swa_model/bonusbelief_output", "swa_model/ownership_output" ], input_name_shape_dict={ #"x": [1, size, size, 22], "swa_model/bin_inputs": [1, size * size, 22], "swa_model/global_inputs": [1, 14], }, target_ios="13" ) </denchmark-code>
Usage of the script is, <denchmark-code>python script_above.py <target pb model> 19 <output mlmodel name> </denchmark-code>
One of inputs of the model above is 1D and would be reshaped to 2D in the model. So I also tried transformed model whose input is 2D like for Core ML 2. I am not quite sure if Core ML 3 eliminates the restriction of inputs or not. The result was same.

Hi. The cause seems that all Const nodes have None as attribute "value" after loading the model. Why? I confirmed that all Const nodes have some values by tensorboard. Please give me any solutions or hints.

<denchmark-link:https://github.com/1duo>@1duo</denchmark-link> san, Now I understood that sess.run in constant_propagation is totally unstable. I changed the code to do sess.run for each query rather than query_list in order to clarify which node is problem. Every run of script raised an exception below by different node. <denchmark-code>tensorflow.python.framework.errors_impl.InvalidArgumentError: Retval[XXX] does not have value </denchmark-code>
It seems that the issue is not related with coremltools but with tensorflow. Could you give me any advices? Thank you.

Hi <denchmark-link:https://github.com/y-ich>@y-ich</denchmark-link> , thanks for the extra debug information! It could be the Switch op that has two outputs, one normal tensor and the other "dead" tensor that fails at sess.run() because it's "dead" and thus does not have value when we try to evaluate in the constant_propogation() function. Could you help to verify it's related to Switch op (by print out the op's name and type that fails for sess.run())? Your model is very large and thus hard to debug so in the meantime, we can work on creating a simple model or a test case that can reproduce this error so we can easily work on a fix and verify.

<denchmark-link:https://github.com/1duo>@1duo</denchmark-link> san, thank you for your advice! Removing Switch ops from query_list and reducing the correspondents of constant_node_num_outputs eliminated "Constant Propagation pass failed". Now I encountered a new problem. It seems that the function _is_NHWC in op_fusions.py does not work well for my model. I will create another issue or hopefully pull request for it.

I made a workaround. <denchmark-link:https://github.com/y-ich/coremltools/tree/constant_propagation>https://github.com/y-ich/coremltools/tree/constant_propagation</denchmark-link>
It works when numbers of dead outputs are in latter part, e.g. original outpus are [0, 1, 2] and dead ones are [1, 2].

I understood that Switches were for batchnorm to switch training or inference in my case. Removing Switches with floating output was not enough for constant propagation. Recognizing Merges connecting with those Switches as constants brings constant propagation further.
